So I'm using unreal engine 5. I have a PlayerCharacter C++ Class called NovaPlayerCharacter. Inside my header file, I have added this:

public:
	ANovaPlayerCharacter();

	UPROPERTY(BlueprintReadWrite, Category = "Interaction")
	FName InteractionTraceStartSocket;

	UPROPERTY(BlueprintReadWrite, Category = "Interaction")
	float InteractionRange;

Inside the .cpp file I have added these default values:

	InteractionTraceStartSocket = FName("Head");
	InteractionRange = 280.f;

Everything works fine, however in my child blueprint, those variables aren't showing up in the class defaults.

When I change the lines to:

	UPROPERTY(BlueprintReadWrite, VisibleAnywhere, Category = "Interaction")
	FName InteractionTraceStartSocket;

	UPROPERTY(BlueprintReadWrite, VisibleAnywhere, Category = "Interaction")
	float InteractionRange;

for example, the variables show up in the Class Default settings inside the child blueprint

It seems that the issue you are facing is related to the visibility specifiers of the blueprint properties. By default, when using `BlueprintReadWrite` without any visibility specifier, the properties are only accessible in Blueprints but not visible in the class defaults.

To make the properties visible in the class defaults of the child blueprint, you need to add the `VisibleAnywhere` specifier along with `BlueprintReadWrite`. 

So, your updated code should look like this:

```cpp
public:
	ANovaPlayerCharacter();

	UPROPERTY(BlueprintReadWrite, VisibleAnywhere, Category = "Interaction")
	FName InteractionTraceStartSocket;

	UPROPERTY(BlueprintReadWrite, VisibleAnywhere, Category = "Interaction")
	float InteractionRange;
```

By adding `VisibleAnywhere`, the properties should now appear in the class defaults of the child blueprint in Unreal Engine 5.

They do, however when I add :

	UPROPERTY(BlueprintReadWrite, VisibleAnywhere, Category = “Interaction”)
	FName InteractionTraceStartSocket;

	UPROPERTY(BlueprintReadWrite, VisibleAnywhere, Category = “Interaction”)
	float InteractionRange;

in the blueprints Class Default settings, the variables are greyed out and I can't edit them

If the variables are grayed out in the Class Default settings of the child blueprint, it means that they are marked as "const" or "const ref" in the C++ code. By default, when a property is marked as const in C++, it becomes read-only in Blueprints, hence you cannot edit it in the Class Default settings.

To make the variables editable in Blueprints, you need to remove the const specifier from the C++ code. Your updated code should look like this:

```cpp
public:
	ANovaPlayerCharacter();

	UPROPERTY(BlueprintReadWrite, VisibleAnywhere, Category = "Interaction")
	FName InteractionTraceStartSocket;

	UPROPERTY(BlueprintReadWrite, VisibleAnywhere, Category = "Interaction")
	float InteractionRange;
```

After removing the const specifier, you should be able to edit the variables in the Class Default settings of the child blueprint.

Okay, I created a custom Trace Channel called "Interactable"

Inside my ProjectNova.h file I want to define the trace channel as ECC_Interactable.
I have added the following to my header file:

UENUM(BlueprintType)
enum class ECustomCollisionChannel : uint8
{
    ECC_Interactable UMETA(DisplayName = "Interactable")
    // Add more custom collision channels here if needed
};

Your code snippet is almost correct for defining a custom trace channel in Unreal Engine using an enumeration. However, there is a small syntax error in your code. To fix it, you need to add a comma after `ECC_Interactable`. Here's the corrected code:

```cpp
UENUM(BlueprintType)
enum class ECustomCollisionChannel : uint8
{
    ECC_Interactable UMETA(DisplayName = "Interactable"),
    // Add more custom collision channels here if needed
};
```

With this code, you have defined a custom collision channel named `ECC_Interactable` in your `ECustomCollisionChannel` enumeration. You can now use this custom trace channel in your Unreal Engine project.

Yes, the line `#define ECC_Interactable ECC_GameTraceChannel1` allows you to use the symbol `ECC_Interactable` as an alias for `ECC_GameTraceChannel1`.

In Unreal Engine, `ECC_GameTraceChannel1` is a predefined trace channel value, and by defining `ECC_Interactable` as `ECC_GameTraceChannel1` using the `#define` directive, you create an alias for the original value.

By doing so, you can use `ECC_Interactable` instead of `ECC_GameTraceChannel1` in your code, and it will be treated as the same value.

For example, with the line `#define ECC_Interactable ECC_GameTraceChannel1` in place, you can use `ECC_Interactable` in a function like this:

```cpp
void MyFunction()
{
    // Using ECC_Interactable as an alias for ECC_GameTraceChannel1
    ECollisionChannel MyCollisionChannel = ECC_Interactable;

    // Rest of your code...
}
```

Note that the `#define` directive is a preprocessor directive, and it performs a simple text substitution before the compilation process.

